Often it has to do with cooking grains (<vocabulary>to cook grains</vocabulary>).
reading_mnemonic: When you cook something, it's like you're a<reading>ttack</reading>ing (たく) the food with boiling water or fire or whatever. Attack the food by cooking it!

examples.en: He calls his clients suckers behind their backs and yet he bobs his head and says flattering things to their faces.

meaning_mnemonic: Even though you have this <kanji>habit</kanji> you're still able to win. That's why this is <vocabulary>And yet</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>though</vocabulary>, and <vocabulary>in spite of</vocabulary>. Because, <vocabulary>in spite of</vocabulary> your bad habit, you still won. Frustrating.

examples.en: Is your country an imperialistic nation?

reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. Will help to know the two words this word is made up of, 帝国 and 主義.

examples.en: Isn’t the girl in the wheelchair ridiculously sexy?

reading_mnemonic: The reading for 車 is the vocab reading, くるま. Then, 椅子 is いす.

examples.en: The sumo wrestler braced himself at the edge of the ring and was able to throw his opponent out.
examples.ja: その力士は土俵際で踏ん張り、相手力士に打っ棄りを食らわせた。

meaning_mnemonic: Remember how 土俵 is a sumo ring? Now you're at its <kanji>edge</kanji>, which means this is the <vocabulary>edge of a sumo ring</vocabulary>. This can also refer to a <vocabulary>last moment</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>critical moment</vocabulary> in time, like the moment before you get pushed out of the ring.
reading_mnemonic: This combines the on'yomi readings in the 土俵 vocab with the kun'yomi reading you learned from the 際 vocab. Just think of these as two familiar vocab words mashed together and you should be good to go!

examples.en: It was just a fluke that I was able to answer the questions on the quiz.

meaning_mnemonic:
When you're <kanji>distract</kanji>ed, everything you do is a <vocabulary>fluke</vocabulary>. You're not focusing, so it all comes down to <vocabulary>chance</vocabulary>.

Note that this word is mostly written in kana only!
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. This uses a different reading than the one you've already learned, so here's a mnemonic to help you:

Somebody was trying to <reading>mug</reading> (まぐ) you, but you managed to escape by pure <vocabulary>chance</vocabulary>! Your escape might have just been a <vocabulary>fluke</vocabulary>, but at least you didn't get mugged!

examples.en: I called the police right after I received the threatening call, but for some reason it seemed like they didn’t want to deal with it.

Note that 脅迫 often involves overt and serious threats that may cross legal boundaries.

examples.en: We have a year's supply of toilet paper stored in our basement.

meaning_mnemonic:
I need something to <kanji>provide</kanji> for me in an emergency, so I'm <kanji>amass</kanji>ing <vocabulary>emergency stores</vocabulary>. I'm building up a <vocabulary>stockpile</vocabulary> of <vocabulary>reserves</vocabulary>, just in case.

備蓄 is a formal word for stockpiling or reserving supplies for future use, especially in preparation for emergencies or shortages. It's commonly used for storing food, water, fuel, or other necessities in case of disasters.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: It's important to eat breakfast and store up energy for your brain.

examples.en: You're asking why I eat pudding every day? I'm storing up fat for the winter.
examples.ja: 何で毎日プリン食べてるかって？冬に向けて脂肪を蓄えてるのよ。

examples.en: He's growing such a splendid mustache.

meaning_mnemonic:
Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>amass</kanji> and the verb vocab version is <vocabulary>to store up</vocabulary> — as in gradually gathering and keeping something so it's there when you need it.

This often relates to storing up food or supplies. In the same vein, it can mean <vocabulary>to amass</vocabulary> a fortune for later use, or <vocabulary>to build up</vocabulary> things like stamina and knowledge to slowly prepare yourself for something. You can even say ヒゲを蓄える (to build up or grow facial hair). Readiness comes in many forms, you know?
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word consists of a kanji with hiragana attached, you can bet that it will use the kun'yomi reading. You didn't learn that reading with this kanji, so here's a mnemonic to help you:

You need <vocabulary>to store up</vocabulary> things, so you <reading>take one</reading> (たくわ) and put it aside, then take one more and put it aside again. Repeat this <vocabulary>to amass</vocabulary> all kinds of things over time. It's the best way <vocabulary>to build up</vocabulary> a nice little stash.

examples.en: Ouch. Watch where you’re going! Don’t look away while you’re walking!
examples.ja: いてぇ。どこに目ぇつけて歩いてるんだ！脇見しながら歩いてんじゃねぇぞ！

meaning_mnemonic: If you look to your <kanji>armpit</kanji> to <kanji>see</kanji> you're <vocabulary>looking away</vocabulary> from where you should be looking. If you're too busy staring at your armpit while you drive, for example, you'll probably get in an accident. So don't look away like this!
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the reading you learned with 脇 and the reading for 見る.

examples.en: She keeps talking about how she passed the audition, but it looks like she only got a supporting role.
examples.ja: 彼女、オーディションに受かったって言いふらしてるけど、ただの脇役みたいだよ。

meaning_mnemonic: If you're on <kanji>armpit</kanji> <kanji>duty</kanji> you're definitely not the lead. You're standing next to the lead's armpit, because you're the <vocabulary>supporting actor</vocabulary>. You're in a <vocabulary>supporting role</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is 脇's reading and 役's reading, put together.

examples.en: He was very close to lying to depositors to prevent a bank run, but in the end he gave up on the attempt.
examples.ja: 彼は取り付け騒ぎを防ぐ為にもう少しで預金者に嘘をつくところだったが、結局未遂に終わった。

meaning_mnemonic: When you try something but can <kanji>not yet</kanji> <kanji>accomplish</kanji> it, it's only an <vocabulary>attempt</vocabulary> that failed or stayed incomplete. That's 未遂, and it's often used in legal contexts for crimes that didn't succeed.

examples.en: I am embarrassed that I failed the execution of the mission.

meaning_mnemonic: Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>punch</kanji>, so the verb means <vocabulary>to punch</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>to strike</vocabulary>, or <vocabulary>to hit</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: Someone is <reading>nag</reading>ging (なぐ) you and nagging you about something. You can't take it any more, so you turn around <vocabulary>to punch</vocabulary> them in the face.

reading_mnemonic: Think of a big ol' <vocabulary>shield</vocabulary>. It's so big it will stand (<reading>立て</reading>) tall right in front of you.

examples.en: I was encouraged by my friend’s support.

examples.en: At the moment I farted, a teardrop fell out of my eyes.
examples.ja: おならをした瞬間、目から涙が零れた。

examples.en: Someone spilled tea on the couch! Who's the guilty one?
examples.ja: ソファに紅茶が零れてるんだけど！誰が犯人だ？

examples.en: A beautiful melody spilled out from the window.
examples.ja: 窓から美しいメロディが零れてきた。

meaning_mnemonic:
This word consists of kanji with hiragana attached. Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb.

This is an intransitive verb, so this verb means <vocabulary>to get spilled</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>to fall out</vocabulary>, or <vocabulary>to overflow</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic:
Since this word has okurigana (hiragana attached to the kanji) you know that it's probably going to be the kun'yomi reading.

Lucky for you, the kanji readings for transitive and intransitive verbs are almost always the same. Once you learn one, you know them both! This reading is the same as 零す.

examples.en: Ah, we're out of staples.
examples.ja: あ、ホッチキスの針、切れちゃった。

examples.en: Wow, that's thick! I wonder if I can staple it together with this stapler?
examples.ja: うわっ、分厚い！このホッチキスでとじれるかな？

examples.en: When stapling Japanese documents, it is common practice to staple the top right corner for vertical writing and the top left corner for horizontal writing.
examples.ja: 日本の書類をホッチキスで止める時は、縦書きの場合は右上、横書きの場合は左上をホッチキスで止めるのが一般的です。

meaning_mnemonic:
This word means <vocabulary>stapler</vocabulary>. It comes from the name of the company that first imported staplers into Japan: Hotchkiss! Here’s a mnemonic to help you remember it:

Ever given a <reading>hot kiss</reading> (ホッチキス) to a <vocabulary>stapler</vocabulary>? Imagine what that feels like, and you'll remember this word forever. Just keep in mind that sometimes it's written as ホチキス, but ホッチキス is more common.
